{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nWith the threshold empirically derived (sibling story), flip the serious-tier code-review criteria from advisory-in-everything-but-name to actually able to BLOCK. Today only the two DET criteria (secret-detection, high-critical-security) can block; all 15 LLM criteria ship blocking_enabled: false at 0.95 — locked as the permissive-rollout invariant by ADR 0036 and pinned by tests/unit/test_impact_model_versioning.py::test_code_review_only_det_security_criteria_are_hard_blocks. The field false-block risk is demonstrably near zero (0 finding-blocks in 162 changes).\n\n- CRITICAL DISTINCTION (the reviewer's catch): `blocking_enabled` lives on CRITERIA (the routing keys in criteria_routing.json: `security`, `api-compat`, `db-migrations`, `deletion-impact`, `tests`, `scope-intent`, …) — NOT on the consequence-BINARIES (`data_loss_without_recovery`, etc.), which are decide.py severity attributes that set a finding's IMPACT, not routing entries. So the flip is: turn `blocking_enabled: true` on the CRITERIA whose Pass-1 findings carry the serious (0.9) binaries.\n\n## What\n- In src/rebar/llm/code_review/criteria_routing.json set `blocking_enabled: true` + `block_threshold` = the derived value (~0.6, per sibling 9f25's crossover analysis) on the serious-tier CRITERIA, per this mapping (serious consequence-binary → owning criterion routing key), to be confirmed against the verifier prompts during implementation:\n  - `security_bypass_not_enforced_elsewhere` → **security**\n  - `data_loss_without_recovery` → **db-migrations**, **deletion-impact**\n  - `unversioned_published_contract_break` → **api-compat**\n  - `safety_net_removal_without_replacement` → **tests**, **deletion-impact**\n  - `silent_wrong_feeding_a_decision` → **scope-intent** (or **security** if its prompt owns it)\n  Only the criteria named by this table (finalized against the prompts) gain blocking; everything else stays advisory at 0.95. The two DET criteria (secret-detection, high-critical-security) stay blocking as-is.\n- Update ADR 0036 (dated note: permissive rollout concluded for the named CRITERIA, evidence attached) and BOTH pinning tests: `tests/unit/test_impact_model_versioning.py::test_code_review_only_det_security_criteria_are_hard_blocks` AND `tests/unit/test_code_review_ws2.py::test_secrets_security_keys_are_the_ws5_blocking_handoff` (line 64: `assert set(blocking) == {\"secret-detection\",\"high-critical-security\"}`) — both must be updated to the new approved blocking set, and each must still assert NO OTHER criterion blocks.\n- Keep pass-3 separation intact: this is a threshold/posture CONFIG change only — no decide.py math changes.\n- NOTE: this depends on 9f25's derived threshold; if 9f25's honest crossover comes out ABOVE 0.54/0.60, AC4's \"#518/#539-class findings now BLOCK\" is revisited with 9f25's actual number (do not force a threshold to satisfy the AC — the epic's Definitions record this contingency).\n\n## Scope\nsrc/rebar/llm/code_review/criteria_routing.json, tests/unit/test_impact_model_versioning.py, tests/unit/test_code_review_ws2.py (the second blocking-set pinning test — test_secrets_security_keys_are_the_ws5_blocking_handoff), docs/adr/0036-*.md, docs/plan-review-gate.md (the cross-gate posture note), tests/unit/test_code_review_blocking_replay.py (self-contained serious-vs-NIT blocking replay). Depends on the derivation story 9f25 (consumes its derived threshold + its code-review derivation/replay script).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] The approved serious-tier CRITERIA (routing keys per the mapping table above) have blocking_enabled: true at the derived block_threshold in criteria_routing.json; all other LLM criteria remain advisory at 0.95.\n- [ ] BOTH pinning tests (test_impact_model_versioning.py::test_code_review_only_det_security_criteria_are_hard_blocks AND test_code_review_ws2.py::test_secrets_security_keys_are_the_ws5_blocking_handoff) are updated to assert the NEW approved blocking set and each fails on any unapproved addition.\n- [ ] ADR 0036 carries a dated enablement note citing derivation ticket 9f25.\n- [ ] A SELF-CONTAINED replay proves #518-class and #539-class findings now BLOCK while false-blocks stay 0 — WITHOUT depending on any sibling's not-yet-built script. Proving artifact (owned by this ticket): a unit test `tests/unit/test_code_review_blocking_replay.py` that (a) loads a small committed fixture of code_review_result_v1-shaped records — a couple of #518-class (importlib code-execution) and #539-class (correctness) findings with their real impacts, plus a set of NIT-shaped findings, and (b) applies the flipped blocking config + derived threshold via the real routing (`reg.threshold_for(...)` / the blocking decision), asserting the serious findings cross the threshold under a now-blocking criterion while the NIT set yields 0 blocks. Proving command: `.venv/bin/pytest tests/unit/test_code_review_blocking_replay.py -q`. (9f25 owns the corpus-wide adjudication + derivation; this AC only proves the config change makes qualifying findings block.) If 9f25's honest threshold cannot make these findings block without false-blocks, this AC is renegotiated against 9f25's data rather than forced.\n- [ ] make lint passes on the change.\n- [ ] make typecheck passes on the change.\n- [ ] make test passes on the change."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783889970861457001,"uuid":"8f55f562-6a9c-461c-bef4-6e8a62929ad0"}